    {
      "id": "facsimile-images",
      "html": "<h2>Facsimile Images</h2><a href=\"ISic001346_tiled.tif\"><img title=\"Photo J. Prag\" src=\"ISic001346_tiled-thumb.tif\"></a><a href=\"ISic001346.jpg\"><img title=\"Photo J. Prag\" src=\"ISic001346-thumb.jpg\"></a><a href=\"ISic001346_rev_tiled.tif\"><img title=\"Photo J. Prag\" src=\"ISic001346_rev_tiled-thumb.tif\"></a><a href=\"ISic001346_rev.jpg\"><img title=\"Photo J. Prag\" src=\"ISic001346_rev-thumb.jpg\"></a>"
    },
    {
      "id": "apparatus",
      "html": "<h4>Apparatus criticus</h4><ul><li><span>  <span>Text based on photograph and previous editors</span>  </span>; </li><li><span class=\"B.1\">B.1: <span>Mommsen TITO S[-]ATAR/ae</span>  </span>; </li><li><span class=\"B.1\">  <span>Walther, Amico, Torremuzza, Ferrara, Kirchhof, Ferrua, Korhonen: ἔτη ις´, μῆνες ε´; Kaibel, Wessel: ἔτη ις´ (vel ιγ´), μῆνες ε´ (vel θ´)</span>  </span><br></li><li><span class=\"B.2\">B.2: <span>Walther, Amico, Torremuzza, Ferrara, Kirchhof, Ferrua, Korhonen: αὐτοῦ; Kaibel, Wessel: αὐτῶν</span>  </span></li></ul>"
    },
    {
      "id": "translation",
      "html": "<h2>English translation</h2><p class=\"translation-author\"><a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0003-3819-8537\">Jonathan Prag</a></p>  <p>Titus Aelius Victorinus lived 16 years, 5 months, 17 days. His dutiful brothers made (this) together with their mother from the legacy of Victorinus ...</p>  "
    },
    {
      "id": "translation",
      "html": "<h2>Italian translation</h2><p class=\"translation-author\"><a href=\"https://orcid.org/0000-0001-5187-5163\">Marta Fogagnolo</a></p>  <p>Titos Aelios Victorinos visse 18 anni, 5 mesi e 17 giorni. I suoi fratelli pietosi hanno realizzato (questo) insieme con la loro madre dagli averi di Vittorino ...</p>  "
    },
    {
      "id": "commentary",
      "html": "<h2>commentary</h2>  <p>Walther and Vallambert (in Cod. Vat. Lat. 6039 f. 85v) describe the relief, in which a bare-headed man with a long tunic was surrounded by two young boys, one riding a horse, the other leading another horse (the names of the boys were inscribed on the relief <span class=\"lang\" lang=\"grc\">ΜΕΜΦΙΣ</span> and <span class=\"lang\" lang=\"grc\">ΔΕΚΕΝΙΟΣ</span>, the latter written right to left). The epitaph was considered to be Christian by the editors before Ferrua because of the cross symbol before <span class=\"lang\" lang=\"grc\">Τίτος</span>. However, the symbol has proven to be later, perhaps modern, since Vallambert in the mid-16th century did not see it. The cross may have been inscribed at a later stage to make the object “more Christian”. Apart from this, there is no other evidence for a Christian provenance of the inscription: the subject of the relief argues rather in favour of a pagan provenance of the document, as Ferrua remarks. The two naked young men near horses may refer to the Dioscuri, just as the expression <span class=\"lang\" lang=\"grc\">ἀδελφοὶ εὐσεβεῖς</span> may refer to another pair of brothers famous in Catania, the <span class=\"lang\" lang=\"la\">Pii fratres</span>, named also in IG 14.502 = <a href=\"http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001323\" target=\"_blank\">ISic001323</a>. The grave could also have been built not by the brothers of the deceased, but “metaphorically” by the <span class=\"lang\" lang=\"la\">Pii fratres</span>, that is by his mother under the protection of the divine brothers.</p>  <p>Korhonen favours a dating to the second half of the 2nd century CE because Titus Aelius was often adopted by freedmen after the reign of Antoninus Pius. For the expression <span class=\"lang\" lang=\"grc\">ἐκ τῶν αὐτοῦ</span> as the equivalent of <span class=\"lang\" lang=\"la\">sua pecunia</span>, see IG 14.574 = <a href=\"http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001393\" target=\"_blank\">ISic001393</a>.</p>  "
    },
    {
      "id": "bibliography",
      "html": "<h2>bibliography</h2>  <ul><li> 9211 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000394\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000394</a>  </li><li> Gualtherus 1624 [1625] <a href=\"http://arachne.uni-koeln.de/item/buchseite/310933\" target=\"_blank\">36</a>  <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001931\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001931</a>  </li><li> Amico 1741 260 no.1 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002186\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002186</a>  </li><li> Castelli 1769 256 no.54 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002084\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002084</a>  </li><li> Castelli 1784 274 no.62 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002083\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002083</a>  </li><li> Ferrara 1829 369 no.3 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002005\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002005</a>  </li><li> Kirchhoff 1877 9477 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001249\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001249</a>  </li><li> Mommsen 1883 <a href=\"http://arachne.uni-koeln.de/books/CILv10pII1883\" target=\"_blank\">1063*</a>  <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000589\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000589</a>  </li><li> Kaibel 1890 <a href=\"https://clio.columbia.edu/catalog/6873760\" target=\"_blank\">527</a>  <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001072\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001072</a>  </li><li> Ferrua 1941 162-164 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001456\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001456</a>  </li><li> Korhonen 2004 52 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000028\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000028</a>  </li></ul>  <ul><li></li></ul>  "
    },
    {
      "id": "handnote",
      "html": " <p>Slightly irregularly disposed letters, with a hedera between the first two words. In the text preserved by Gualtherus lunate epsilon, sigma and cursive omega are recorded, and interpuncts before the numerals.</p> Line 1  30-37  Interlineation line 1 to 2  not recorded  "
    },
